        "text": "The Left Behind series is a collection of sixteen books, and they were written by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins. Here is all you need to know about the reading order.\n\nWho is the author?\n\nThe Left Behind book series was created by Tim LaHaye and Jerry B. Jenkins. Tim LaHaye, or Timothy Francis LaHaye, was born in 1926, and he wrote over 80 books, with a focus on both Christian fiction and non-fiction.\n\nThe other writer, Jerry Bruce Jenkins, was born in 1949 and wrote over 200 books in various genres. The duo first started working on the Left Behind series in 1995, and it has since been transformed into different media as well, such as movies, graphic novels (published by Tyndale House), and video games.\n\nThe Left Behind series was on the New York Times bestseller list and still remains a popular read among Christians and unbelievers alike.\n\nAbout the series\n\nThe story explores a seven-year conflict between an underground group of converts called the Tribulation Force and a Global Community. It was based on the books of Revelation, Daniel, Isaiah, and Ezekiel.\n\nThe leader of this group is named Nicolae Carpathia, and he is also the Antichrist. The story uses elements from the Bible, and it is a series of Christian novels. The story in Left Behind is the story of the end times, and it is set in the contemporary era.\n\nOne of the main themes and questions is whether a Christian can have a mark of the beast and still be saved in the end.\n\nThere is also the Left Behind: The Kids series that follows the same story, but it is written for teenagers, and the main characters are kids. There is also a series of movies starring Bruce Barnes, Kirk Cameron, Brad Johnson, Gordon Currie, Janaya Stephens, and others.\n\nThe original series covered the first two books. You can also check Amazon’s Goodreads and see the positive reviews. That will be enough of a sign to check out the series.\n\nPublication order of the series\n\nIf you are interested in learning more about the Left Behind series, you will need to know the proper reading order.\n\nLeft Behind (1995)\n\nLeft Behind: A Novel of the Earth’s Last Days is the full name of the book, and it was published in 1995. It started the Left Behind series, and it introduced the main characters and themes. It is set on the day of the Rapture and the following two weeks.\n\nTribulation Force (1996)\n\nTribulation Force: The Continuing Drama of Those Left Behind is the second book in the series, and it was published in 1996. The story follows events after the first book and everything that happened after the Rapture.\n\nDuring the Tribulation, it is said that God will rain down judgment on the world for seven years.\n\nNicolae (1997)\n\nNicolae: The Rise of Antichrist is the third book in the series, and it was published in 1997. The events of the book happen between eighteen and twenty-one months into the Tribulation, and the readers will learn more about the main antagonist.\n\nSoul Harvest (1998)\n\nSoul Harvest: The World Takes Sides covers the next eight months into the Tribulation and all the challenges the main characters will face. This includes Rayford Steele, Amanda White, Chloe Steele, Buck Williams, and others.\n\nApollyon (1999)\n\nApollyon: The Destroyer Is Unleashed is the fifth book in the series, and it continues the story from Soul Harvest. In fact, the prologue of the book is the last two pages of the previous installment.\n\nAssassins (1999)\n\nAssassins: Assignment: Jerusalem, Target: Antichrist was published in 1999, and the events in the story are spread between thirty-eight and forty-two months into the Tribulation. The story starts with Rayford Steele and his moral dilemma, which can change everything.\n\nThe Indwelling (2000)\n\nThe Indwelling: The Beast Takes Possession is the seventh published book in the series, and it goes from forty-two months into the Tribulation to the beginning of the Great Tribulation.\n\nThe Mark (2000)\n\nThe Mark: The Beast Rules the World is the eighth published book, and it explores events deeper into the Great Tribulation. In the series of unexpected events, the protagonists will face new challenges.\n\nDesecration (2001)\n\nDesecration: Antichrist Takes the Throne was published in 2001, and it is the tenth book in the series in the publishing order. Nicolae Carpathia continues his reign, and he returns to Jerusalem. He wants to claim the city as his own temple.\n\nThe Remnant (2002)\n\nThe Remnant: On the Brink of Armageddon continues after the events in Desecration, and it covers events two-and-a-half years into the Great Tribulation. Armageddon approaches, and Nicolae Carpathia has no plans of stopping his destructive plans.\n\nArmageddon (2003)\n\nArmageddon: The Cosmic Battle of the Ages, and is the eleventh published book in the Left Behind series. The events of the novel all lead to the Glorious Appearing, and the main characters will need to find a way to fight Nicolae Carpathia.\n\nGlorious Appearing (2004)\n\nGlorious Appearing: The End of Days is the twelfth book in the series, and the war of Armageddon is close to the end. True believers are awaiting the return of Jesus Christ as the story reaches its climax.\n\nThe Rising (2005)\n\nThe Rising: Antichrist is Born: Before They Were Left Behind is the thirteenth published book, but the events happen before the first story. It is the first of the prequel novels, and it is worth checking out if you enjoy the series.\n\nThe Regime (2005)\n\nThe Regime: Evil Advances: Before They Were Left Behind is the second prequel book, and it was published in 2005. The events in The Regime continue the story from the Rising, and it is the second book in the prequel trilogy.\n\nThe Rapture (2005)\n\nThe Rapture: In the Twinkling of an Eye: Countdown to Earth’s Last Days is the final book in the prequel trilogy, and the events of the story lead directly to the beginning of the series in Left Behind.\n\nKingdom Come (2007)\n\nKingdom Come: The Final Victory is the final book in the series, and it continues from Glorious Appearing. The events of the story lead to the last day of the Millennium, and it is the culmination of the story.\n\nChronological order\n\nOne way you could go through the story is in chronological order. This means that you will not start with the first book but with the thirteenth one instead."
